reviewText: A Fairly Odd Movie: Grow Up, Timmy Turner!(2011) is a live action TV movie produced by Nickelodeon and directed by Savage Steve Holland(creator of Eek the Cat). The Fairly Oddparents is an animated TV show created by Butch Hartman. A Fairly Odd Movie took a lot of criticism from Fairly Oddparents fans and movie and TV critics. The TV movie did well with high ratings and it spawned a sequel, A Fairly Odd Christmas(2012). This film was going to get a theatrical release, but it went straight to TV and cable. I purchased my copy on a "special DVD-R release"! A Fairly Odd Movie Grow Up Timmy Turner is fun and loaded with vibrant colors, but it's campy, packed with noise and extremely fast paced! It's like adding speed, sugar and coffee to a broken merry-go-round! In the film, an adult Timmy Turner(Drake Bell) has to rescue Tootie(Daniella Monet) and his fairy godparents without help from magic tricks. They're being held hostage by an evil rich guy. There's a little bit of toilet humor. A teacher loses control of his bowels and a bird poops on a man's bald head! Jason Alexander from Seinfeld plays a flesh and blood version of godparent Cosmo. Drake Bell is decent as Timmy Turner. Daniella Monet is superb as Tootie. She's extremely sexy, yet she still has a wholesome, girl next door warmth. Daniella Monet could be good as Ann Marie in a modern Hollywood reboot of That Girl. A Fairly Odd Movie is bad, but not a turkey. It's somewhere between Gone With the Wind(1939) and Monster A Go Go(1965). A Fairly Odd Movie Grow Up Timmy Turner is a decent TV movie.
Title: Fairly Odd Movie "Grow Up, Timmy Turner!"

reviewText: It's loud,obnoxious and annoying. There's never a silent moment where the film can just breath or take a break. It's nothing but noise. The life lesson in this TV Film was shoved in our faces so many times that I couldn't take it anymore. The comedy while it worked well in the cartoon, it failed in the live action movie. The villains are either an tired old cliche like oil tycoon or an insufferable cartoony nutacse like Mr.Crocker and Vicki. Infact,the whole acting is over-the-top and cartoony. The story is tried and cliche too. The jokes are lazy,tried and dumb. Not to mention there's also slime humor which I HATE so much. At least with The Last Airbender movie there were some silent moments,villain(s) that were subtle,a subtle morale and best of all, no smile humor.  The only good thing about his film is the guy who played Timmy's dad(who also voiced Timmy's dad in the cartoon) but even that fails to help the movie in the long run. I give this "film" a 0 out of 10.
Title: Fairly Odd Movie "Grow Up, Timmy Turner!"

reviewText: I remember watching Timmy Turner when I was growing up and loved the show. So I introduced it to my kids. They love Fairly Odd Parents we watch it every day. So when I came across this I just knew I had to have it. My kids & I couldn't wait for it to get here so we could watch. When it did we watched it immediatley. My kids loved it & wacthed it 3 or 4 more times that day. Me, well I was disappointed. I guess I expected better. I expected to see Vicki (the babysitter), A.J. (Timmy's best friend), etc... It focused more on Timmy falling in love with Trixy (vicki's little sister). The fairies was great you couldn't have asked for better actors to play Wanda & Cosmo. My kids loved it and watches it all the time. Myself would watch with them but if I had to get up and fold laundry or cook dinner that it wouldn't break my heart to miss the movie.
Title: Fairly Odd Movie "Grow Up, Timmy Turner!"

reviewText: The Fairly OddParents has seen a gradual drop in quality over the years, in which the humor has lost its luster and grown tiresomely repetitive, the characters' unintelligence has been enhanced to an irritating degree, and the amusement and flair has just receded with time. This film is no exception. The special effects are corny, certain actors playing certain characters noted for particular hallmarks, distinctive personalities, and unique quirks (i.e. Vicky, Crocker, Jorgen) don't do a very good job in their roles, and the whole film is just one giant pile of cheese. The computer animation for the fairies is cheesy as well--their crowns are droopy as if they are floating above their heads by invisible strings and Wanda's eyelashes are also droopy. But that is beside the point. All this film revolves around is a twenty-year-old fifth grader drawn between his true love and childhood fairy godparents, and he only can have either one or the other. At this same time, he's being conspired against by a crazed elementary school teacher and a wealthy oil tycoon. It is nothing especially entertaining, there are not many notable good qualities at all, and it is just a bad, poorly-produced, stupid situation comedy episode practically. I can recall news that this originally had been planned as the series finale and feeling badly because I hate good-byes. Now I would not mind seeing the Fairly OddParents being cancelled once and for all before it can get any worse. Things just are not the same.Let me just state that just because things can change with time doesn't necessarily make them bad. Sometimes it is a good thing, even if the thing that changed was already nice to begin with. However, the Fairly OddParents has changed in an annoying and unentertaining way. This film is not worth it. If you love this program, why not simply purchase episodes from the earlier or middle seasons, before the deterioration in quality? The newer episodes are bad.
Title: Fairly Odd Movie "Grow Up, Timmy Turner!"
